title: Why a certain stem cell produces only the same cell types and not any other cell types?
---

DNA is the same in each and every cell of the body. If we have the same DNA blueprint in each and every cell of the body, then why do they perform different functions. The protein coded by the liver cell is different from that coded by the kidney cell. The simple answer is that cells must switch on or off certain sets of genes according to their functions. The system that sets certain sets of genes on or off must pass on from the parent cell to the daughter cell every time there is a cell division.

This creates a paradox as only DNA is material that carries genetic information and DNA stays the same in different cell types in one individual. So, it means that some modifications responsible for gene expression must pass on from the parent cell to the daughter cell and these modifications must not change the original nature of the DNA code. This thing comes under another branch of genetics which is known as epigenetics.

Many types of epigenetic modification have been discovered and the research is still in progress. The first epigenetic modification identified was DNA methylation. In DNA methylation, a methyl group gets attached to the fifth carbon of the base-pair C. The C is followed by G. This is called CpG motifs. This methyl group doesn't alter the genetic sequence. It has an effect only on gene expression. The CpG motifs are majorly present in the promoter region of the gene. The region is called CpG island. The level of DNA methylation in the CpG island is low when that gene is inactive. Suppose a cell type doesn't require a certain protein for its functioning, then in the promoter region of the gene which codes for that protein, the level of DNA methylation will be increased. There are many other ways of controlling gene expression also.

