Adrian Bird is widely known as the godfather of DNA methylation. Now, the question to wonder here is how DNA methylation controls gene expression. Adrian Bird discovered how DNA methylation switches genes off. He showed that when DNA is methylated, it binds a protein MECP2 (Methyl CpG binding protein) to CpG island. Once it binds, it stops DNA transcription machinery from binding to the promoter region, and thus mRNA can't be produced.

Another question that arises here is how does the pattern of DNA ethylation pass from the mother cell to the daughter cell? This is done by using DNA methyltransferase (DNMT). When replication occurs in the DNA methylated region, DNMT recognizes if CpG motifs are only methylated on one strand and replace the missing methylation on the newly copied strand. Therefore, the daughter cell has the same DNA methylation pattern as that of the parent cell. As a result, a certain cell produces cells of only certain types in spite of being the same genetic material in all cell types.
